<h1 class="text-3xl md:text-4xl font-bold text-white mb-2 leading-tight">Scrabble Glossary</h1>
<p class="text-sm text-gray-400 mb-8 not-prose">Word of the Day · 2-letter words</p>

<p class="text-sm text-gray-500 mb-6">Published June 15, 2026 · 7 min read</p>

<p class="text-lg leading-relaxed mb-8">Scrabble has its own language. Walk into any club or tournament and you will hear players discussing "leaves", "hooks", "phoneys", and "bingo stems." This glossary defines the essential terms so you can follow the conversation and level up your game understanding.</p>

<div class="grid grid-cols-3 gap-4 my-8 p-4 rounded-lg border border-amber-500/30 bg-amber-950/10">
  <div class="text-center"><span class="text-xl font-bold text-amber-400">25+</span><br><span class="text-xs text-gray-400">Terms Defined</span></div>
  <div class="text-center"><span class="text-xl font-bold text-amber-400">A-Z</span><br><span class="text-xs text-gray-400">Organised</span></div>
  <div class="text-center"><span class="text-xl font-bold text-amber-400">All Levels</span><br><span class="text-xs text-gray-400">Beginner to Expert</span></div>
</div>

<h2 class="text-xl font-light text-amber-600 dark:text-amber-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-amber-400 pl-4">Core Game Terms</h2>

<p>These are the foundational terms every player encounters from their first game onwards:</p>

<div class="space-y-3 my-6">
  <div class="p-3 rounded border border-purple-500/30 bg-purple-950/20 hover:border-purple-400 transition-colors">
    <span class="font-semibold text-purple-300">Bingo</span> — Playing all 7 tiles in a single turn, earning a 50-point bonus. The highest-impact play in Scrabble.
  </div>
  <div class="p-3 rounded border border-purple-500/30 bg-purple-950/20 hover:border-purple-400 transition-colors">
    <span class="font-semibold text-purple-300">Blank</span> — A wild tile (2 in the bag) that can represent any letter but scores zero points. The most valuable tile in the game.
  </div>
  <div class="p-3 rounded border border-purple-500/30 bg-purple-950/20 hover:border-purple-400 transition-colors">
    <span class="font-semibold text-purple-300">Challenge</span> — Questioning the validity of an opponent's word. If invalid, they lose their turn. If valid, the challenger loses their next turn (in some rule sets).
  </div>
  <div class="p-3 rounded border border-purple-500/30 bg-purple-950/20 hover:border-purple-400 transition-colors">
    <span class="font-semibold text-purple-300">Exchange</span> — Swapping 1-7 tiles with the bag instead of playing a word. Costs your entire turn but can rescue a terrible rack.
  </div>
  <div class="p-3 rounded border border-purple-500/30 bg-purple-950/20 hover:border-purple-400 transition-colors">
    <span class="font-semibold text-purple-300">Rack</span> — The holder displaying your 7 tiles. Only you can see your rack during play.
  </div>
  <div class="p-3 rounded border border-purple-500/30 bg-purple-950/20 hover:border-purple-400 transition-colors">
    <span class="font-semibold text-purple-300">Tile Bag</span> — The cloth bag containing 100 letter tiles at game start. Players draw blindly to replenish their rack.
  </div>
</div>

<h2 class="text-xl font-light text-amber-600 dark:text-amber-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-amber-400 pl-4">Strategy & Technique Terms</h2>

<p>Once you move past casual play, these terms describe the strategies that separate good players from great ones:</p>

<div class="overflow-x-auto my-6">
<table class="w-full text-sm">
  <thead><tr class="bg-gray-100 dark:bg-gray-800"><th class="p-2 text-left">Term</th><th class="p-2 text-left">Definition</th><th class="p-2 text-left">Example</th></tr></thead>
  <tbody>
    <tr><td class="p-2 font-medium">Hook</td><td class="p-2">Adding a letter before or after an existing word to form a new word</td><td class="p-2">Adding S to CARE → CARES, or H to EAR → HEAR</td></tr>
    <tr class="bg-gray-50 dark:bg-gray-800/50"><td class="p-2 font-medium">Leave</td><td class="p-2">The tiles remaining on your rack after making a play</td><td class="p-2">Playing TRAIN from TRAINED leaves ED</td></tr>
    <tr><td class="p-2 font-medium">Parallel Play</td><td class="p-2">Playing a word alongside an existing word, creating multiple 2-letter combinations</td><td class="p-2">Placing MINT above AREA, making MA, IR, NE, TA</td></tr>
    <tr class="bg-gray-50 dark:bg-gray-800/50"><td class="p-2 font-medium">Fishing</td><td class="p-2">Making a low-scoring play to keep tiles that might form a bingo next turn</td><td class="p-2">Playing just AT from SATIRE to keep S,I,R,E,? for a bingo draw</td></tr>
    <tr><td class="p-2 font-medium">Dump</td><td class="p-2">Playing a low-scoring word primarily to get rid of bad tiles</td><td class="p-2">Playing QI just to remove the Q from your rack</td></tr>
    <tr class="bg-gray-50 dark:bg-gray-800/50"><td class="p-2 font-medium">Spread</td><td class="p-2">The cumulative point difference across tournament games (tiebreaker)</td><td class="p-2">Winning 450-380 gives you +70 spread</td></tr>
  </tbody>
</table>
</div>

<h2 class="text-xl font-light text-amber-600 dark:text-amber-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-amber-400 pl-4">Board Position Terms</h2>

<p>Understanding board geography is essential for both offensive and defensive play:</p>

<div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-4 my-6">
  <div class="p-4 rounded-lg border border-green-500/30 bg-green-950/10">
    <h3 class="font-semibold text-green-400 mb-2">Premium Squares</h3>
    <ul class="text-sm text-gray-300 space-y-1 list-disc list-inside">
      <li><strong>DL</strong> — Double Letter Score (light blue)</li>
      <li><strong>TL</strong> — Triple Letter Score (dark blue)</li>
      <li><strong>DW</strong> — Double Word Score (pink)</li>
      <li><strong>TW</strong> — Triple Word Score (red)</li>
      <li><strong>Star</strong> — Centre square (counts as DW)</li>
    </ul>
  </div>
  <div class="p-4 rounded-lg border border-blue-500/30 bg-blue-950/10">
    <h3 class="font-semibold text-blue-400 mb-2">Board Zones</h3>
    <ul class="text-sm text-gray-300 space-y-1 list-disc list-inside">
      <li><strong>Hotspot</strong> — Open premium square anyone can reach</li>
      <li><strong>Lane</strong> — An open row/column leading to a TW</li>
      <li><strong>Dead zone</strong> — Blocked area with no scoring potential</li>
      <li><strong>Floater</strong> — Isolated word with open hooks</li>
    </ul>
  </div>
</div>

<h2 class="text-xl font-light text-amber-600 dark:text-amber-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-amber-400 pl-4">Competitive & Tournament Terms</h2>

<p>These terms come up in club and tournament settings where formal rules and rating systems apply:</p>

<div class="space-y-3 my-6">
  <div class="p-3 rounded border border-purple-500/30 bg-purple-950/20 hover:border-purple-400 transition-colors">
    <span class="font-semibold text-purple-300">Phoney</span> — A word played that is not in the official dictionary. Stays on board if unchallenged.
  </div>
  <div class="p-3 rounded border border-purple-500/30 bg-purple-950/20 hover:border-purple-400 transition-colors">
    <span class="font-semibold text-purple-300">Clock</span> — The chess clock used in tournaments. Each player gets 25 minutes; overtime costs 10 points per minute.
  </div>
  <div class="p-3 rounded border border-purple-500/30 bg-purple-950/20 hover:border-purple-400 transition-colors">
    <span class="font-semibold text-purple-300">Rating</span> — A numerical ranking (similar to chess Elo) showing competitive strength. Club players range from 800-1200; experts 1600+.
  </div>
  <div class="p-3 rounded border border-purple-500/30 bg-purple-950/20 hover:border-purple-400 transition-colors">
    <span class="font-semibold text-purple-300">Tile Tracking</span> — Keeping a written record of which tiles have been played to deduce opponent's rack.
  </div>
  <div class="p-3 rounded border border-purple-500/30 bg-purple-950/20 hover:border-purple-400 transition-colors">
    <span class="font-semibold text-purple-300">Endgame</span> — The phase after the bag empties when both players can deduce remaining tiles with certainty.
  </div>
  <div class="p-3 rounded border border-purple-500/30 bg-purple-950/20 hover:border-purple-400 transition-colors">
    <span class="font-semibold text-purple-300">Q-stick</span> — Being stuck with the Q tile at game end, costing 10 penalty points.
  </div>
</div>

<h2 class="text-xl font-light text-amber-600 dark:text-amber-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-amber-400 pl-4">Dictionary & Word Study Terms</h2>

<p>Players who study the dictionary encounter these terms describing word properties and relationships:</p>

<div class="overflow-x-auto my-6">
<table class="w-full text-sm">
  <thead><tr class="bg-gray-100 dark:bg-gray-800"><th class="p-2 text-left">Term</th><th class="p-2 text-left">Meaning</th></tr></thead>
  <tbody>
    <tr><td class="p-2 font-medium">SOWPODS</td><td class="p-2">The international tournament dictionary (Collins Scrabble Words) — ~280,000 words</td></tr>
    <tr class="bg-gray-50 dark:bg-gray-800/50"><td class="p-2 font-medium">TWL</td><td class="p-2">Tournament Word List used in North America — ~187,000 words</td></tr>
    <tr><td class="p-2 font-medium">Bingo Stem</td><td class="p-2">A 6-letter combination that forms many 7-letter words (e.g., SATIRE, RETINA)</td></tr>
    <tr class="bg-gray-50 dark:bg-gray-800/50"><td class="p-2 font-medium">Anagram</td><td class="p-2">A word formed by rearranging all letters of another word (LISTEN → SILENT)</td></tr>
    <tr><td class="p-2 font-medium">Front Hook</td><td class="p-2">A letter that can be added before a word to make a new word (B + EACH = BEACH)</td></tr>
    <tr class="bg-gray-50 dark:bg-gray-800/50"><td class="p-2 font-medium">Back Hook</td><td class="p-2">A letter added after a word (FARM + S = FARMS, or FARM + ED = FARMED)</td></tr>
  </tbody>
</table>
</div>

<div class="p-4 rounded-lg border border-indigo-500/30 bg-indigo-950/10 my-6">
  <p class="text-sm text-indigo-400 font-medium mb-1">💡 Learning Path</p>
  <p class="text-sm text-gray-300">Start by learning the core game terms, then add strategy terms as your play improves. Tournament terms can wait until you join a club. The vocabulary grows naturally with experience.</p>
</div>

